<br>
although i am a fan of at least attempting to not be a total oxygen sponge when posting an opinion, that quote is amazing.<br>
<br>
<br>
that being said i would like to post a short essay i wrote in high school for my grammar writing class.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>capital letters</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> </div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--><br>
<br>
i have often pondered the purpose of capital letters. upper case letters only seem to serve the purpose of adding another dimension for grammar students to learn correct usage of. sentences can be completely understood without the use of capital letters. <br>
<br>
the simple fact that capital letters are not used in speech shows that thoughts can be clearly conveyed without capital letters. humans have no troubles deciphering verbal messages because capital letters have no effects on the meanings of sentences. if a live speech were to be transcribed verbatim into two copies, one using correct capitalization; another using no capitalization at all, the non-capitalized copy’s meaning would suffer no loss or change in meaning.<br>
<br>
at the beginning of each sentence the first word is to be capitalized. this redundancy is akin to phrases such as: “seven a.m. in the morning”, “last summer i went during the summer” and “rising up”. the end of each sentence is denoted by a period; therefore the forcing of each word after a period to be capitalized is repetitive.<br>
<br>
proper nouns are unnecessarily dignified by capitalization. hawaii is no different than Hawaii, doctor scott is no different than Doctor Scott, and pepsi is no different than Pepsi. proper nouns are already dignified by their specificity. hawaii is clearly distinguished from island, doctor scott is clearly distinguished from physician, and pepsi is clearly distinguished from pop.<br>
<br>
capitalization is unused in speech, repetitive at the beginning of sentences, and unnecessary to differentiate between proper and common nouns. if capital letters ever had a useful place in writing, they have become vestiges of rhetoric. capital letters serve no purpose and should be abolished from use.<br>
<br>
<br>
