<br>
Wow, this has got to be one of the most important men I've never heard of.  Not only has everyone in the Western world who has put pen to paper in the last thousand years been influenced by him, he was the first to codify the liberal arts (grammar, rhetoric, logic, arithmatic, geometry, astromony, and music) and set up modern schools.  He was the force behind the Carolingian Renaissance that pulled Europe out of the dark ages.  Without Alcuin Europe and Christianity might have ended up an interesting footnote in a world centered somewhere in Asia. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub169.ezboard.com/bmtboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=yalum>Yalum</A> at: 1/3/03 2:49:34 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#102960><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub169.ezboard.com/bmtboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=caerollil>Caerollil</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Qeynos Newbie</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#628CBC>(1/3/03 2:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub169.ezboard.com/fmtboardsfrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=476.topic&index=51>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: ...</span><hr size=1> Clemens.  Samuel Langhorn Clemens.  <br>
